ðŸ‘‰ For which noise intensity does it become unrecognisable?

You may need noise intensities larger than 1. Why?

11.1 Î¼sanswer_about_noise_intensity

The image is unrecognisable with intensity around 5, although difficult to discern above about 3. At any noise level, the dark region in the upper-left corner of the image is vaguely discernable â€“ this is because the clamping operation is keeping close to half of those pixels dark. Similarly the most discernable features of Philip are the eyes and nose, which are dark and discernable. The right ear and shadow near the right of his chest are also dark, but harder to discern a dog from.

No individual color appears to have a major effect on overall recognition, suggesting that contrast between light-and-dark is the major discerning factor. If we had an image that was deficient in certain color components it may be easier to discern color effects.

Playing around with Hue highlights the effect of clamping: to avoid clamping all colors to red (at 0 and 360 degree hue) I wrapped the angle around. With wrap-around the image turns to complete noise when the noise intensity is at 0.5 (hue spans +/- 0.5 of full range, or 100% total span).

Without further statistical analysis, it's difficult to say how much the effect of a uniformly-distributed random variable on 3 independent color channels affects the overall appearance.

Exercise 3 - Convolutions

As we have seen in the videos, we can produce cool effects using the mathematical technique of convolutions. We input one image M and get a new image Mâ€² back.

Conceptually we think of M as a matrix. In practice, in Julia it will be a Matrix of color objects, and we may need to take that into account. Ideally, however, we should write a generic function that will work for any type of data contained in the matrix.

A convolution works on a small window of an image, i.e. a region centered around a given point (i,j). We will suppose that the window is a square region with odd side length 2â„“+1, running from âˆ’â„“,â€¦,0,â€¦,â„“.

The result of the convolution over a given window, centred at the point (i,j) is a single number; this number is the value that we will use for Mi,jâ€². (Note that neighbouring windows overlap.)

To get started let's restrict ourselves to convolutions in 1D. So a window is just a 1D region from âˆ’â„“ to â„“.

Exercise 3.2

We need to decide how to handle the boundary conditions, i.e. what happens if we try to access a position in the vector v beyond 1:n. The simplest solution is to assume that vi is 0 outside the original vector; however, this may lead to strange boundary effects.

A better solution is to use the closest value that is inside the vector. Effectively we are extending the vector and copying the extreme values into the extended positions. (Indeed, this is one way we could implement this; these extra positions are called ghost cells.)

Exercise 4.4

ðŸ‘‰ Create a Sobel edge detection filter.

Here, we will need to create two separate filters that separately detect edges in the horizontal and vertical directions:

Gx=([121]âŠ—[1 0 âˆ’1])âˆ—A=[10âˆ’120âˆ’210âˆ’1]âˆ—AGy=([10âˆ’1]âŠ—[1 2 1])âˆ—A=[121000âˆ’1âˆ’2âˆ’1]âˆ—A

Here A is the array corresponding to your image. We can think of these as derivatives in the x and y directions.

Then we combine them by finding the magnitude of the gradient (in the sense of multivariate calculus) by defining

Gtotal=Gx2+Gy2.

For simplicity you can choose one of the "channels" (colours) in the image to apply this to.
